<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06257161 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06257161 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MULTIPLE; DRUG; CRIME; ARREST; SANTA-CRUZ  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Trying to eliminate narcotics sales in what the district attorney branded the&quot;drug-infested&quot; Beach Flats area of Santa Cruz, police arrested 50 people in asweep through that and other neighborhoods Thursday.;    Officers said theyhoped the sweep would have a major impact on the epidemic of illegal drugsales in Beach Flats -- described by District Attorney Art Danner as &quot;the lastarea in Santa Cruz County where you can actually see drug deals going on onstreet corners.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  POLICE NAB 50 IN DRUG SWEEP  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Most of those arrested -- described by Deputy Police Chief Steve Belcher aslow- and mid-level street dealers -- were charged with felonies, includingcocaine sales, possession of cocaine for sale and being convicted felons inpossession of firearms.;    Indictments issued;  Danner said 11 of the arrestswere on indictments issued by the county grand jury last Friday. Another ninepeople who were indicted remain to be picked up, he said.;    Ron Brooks,director of the County Narcotics Enforcement Team, said the sweep followed afour-month investigation that included many purchases of cocaine by undercoveragents.;    He said Thursday's sweep involved 70 police officers from SantaCruz County agencies and nearby departments. It began with a briefing at theSanta Cruz police station at 6 a.m. and continued through the morning.;   Brooks said agents confiscated $5,000 in cash, 5 ounces of cocaine valued atmore than $16,000, and an ounce and a half of heroin with a street value of$8,000.;    Not all 50 arrests were in the Beach Flats neighborhood. Severalpeople were arrested at four Live Oak dwellings as well as in the EmelineStreet area, investigators said.;    Connections studied;  Although Brookshesitated to describe the 50 as members of a &quot;ring,&quot; he said there wereindications the dealers and their sources of supply were at least looselyorganized.;    &quot;We feel there is a strong connection between most of them,&quot; hesaid.;    He added that bigger dealers &quot;tend to insulate themselves fromstreet dealers.&quot;;    Belcher said he hoped the arrests, plus follow-up work bya special police unit assigned to patrol Beach Flats, would substantiallyreduce drug sales in the neighborhood.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  LEE QUARNSTROM, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Santa Cruz/Monterey  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910913  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  354  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, September 13, 199100257161,SJ1  </DATELINE><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>